The Triumphs Of Fame and Honour

TEI:msItem.TEI:docImprint: ¶ Imprinted at London 1634. Printer Uncertain. The title page does not indicate a printer, but the show was entered into the Stationer’s Register on 14 October 1634 by Henry Gosson, publisher of over sixty of Taylor’s works. However, Gosson was a publisher and did not own a press (Finlayson 114-115).
TEI:msItem.TEI:filiation: While Taylor never authored another Mayoral Show, Taylor’s Pastorall (1624) a work combining verse and prose, connects with the show’s fifth pageant of Endimion, highlighting the importance of the Clothworkers’ Company and role of the craftsmen (Finlayson 114; A Transcript of the Registers 302).
One of only six Lord Mayor’s Shows (1588, 1604, 1612, 1613, 1616, 1634) entered into the Stationer’s Register prior to the Civil War (Finlayson 115).

Thomas Heywood’s Londini Sinus Salutis, or, Londons Harbour of Health and Happiness (1635) is the only other extant Mayoral show printed in octavo format. Printed by Robert Raworth. Lacks ornaments, intials, and type pieces that would link it to the printing of The Triumphs of Fame and Honour.

TEI:supportDesc.TEI:support: Paper, vertical chainlines 22mm apart. No watermark.
TEI:supportDesc.TEI:extent:
Leaves are closely cropped, varying in size.
160 100
TEI:supportDesc.TEI:foliation: Contemporary foliation. A3-4, Twixt; A-B, The; B3-4, More; FINIS.
TEI:supportDesc.TEI:collation: In the only copy recorded the leaves have been detached and mounted on guards, and it is impossible to tell which should be conjugate. It is, therefore, uncertain whether B was a full sheet (with B7,8 blank and missing) or whether it was a quire of six (one fold having been removed)(Greg #495a). Printed in octavo format, Taylor’s pageant book departs from the quarto format typically used for Mayoral Shows.
TEI:supportDesc.TEI:condition: Somewhat poor. Significant wear along the top edge obscures the ornamental decorations, but the fore edge remains in good condition. B2 bears a dark stain along the gutter, possibly pointing to damage incurred during rebinding. Bookworm damage is not observable in the facsimile but noted by Finlayson as being throughout, notably on A2r and B6v (116). Foxing on B6, eroding through B4, B5.

TEI:layout.TEI:fw: Running titles mark the Epistle Dedicatory and the main text. Subtitles mark other significant divisions.
A3 located in the center margin, A4 located center, middle of the page. B, signed right of center, above ornaments.

TEI:typeDesc.TEI:typeNote: Main text in roman type with Epistle Dedicatory in italic. Section titles given for the speeches, the only set of stage directions, and the pageant explanation which are centered, italic, and given a separate line. The speeches of Thetis (A5v) and London (A7v) lack section titles.

TEI:decoDesc.TEI:decoNote: A row of floral bar ornaments line the head and foot of each page with irregular spacing and orientation. More elaborate ornamentation precedes the Epistle Dedicatory and the opening of the Mayoral Show, combining printers’ flowers and bar ornaments. One woodcut initial T begins the text, resulting in the error TThe.

TEI:bindingDesc.TEI:binding: The leaves have been detached and mounted on guards.Taylor’s printed show is currently bound as the first of nineteen items in an early nineteenth-century, brown leather binding. Fifteen items by Taylor, fourteen of which represent pseudo-political works of the 1640s. Remaining four offer responses to Taylor’s political propaganda (Hill 157). Spine embossed in gold with TAYLOR THE WATER POET and five images of a man in a row boat (Finlayson 117). The cover is embossed with the monogram of the John Rylands Library in gold.

TEI:history.TEI:provenance: While the binding is embossed with the John Rylands monogram, which was the practice of Mrs. Rylands, it was unusual for books to be completely rebound when entering the collection. The binding is therefore considered to be a product of the Spencer Collection(Finlayson 117).

The Spencer Collection was purchased for the John Rylands Library by Mrs. Enriqueta Augustina Rylands, the Library’s founder, from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl of Spencer. No records indicate when the Spencer Collection obtained the item, but the Spencer’s book-sellers’ and book-binders’ bills at the Department of Manuscripts in the British Library may yet provide evidence of the sale.

At the sale of James West’s library in 1773, the auctioneer’s catalogue lists the sale of Three ditto [Triumphs], in the Reighn of Cha. I. Rob. Parkhurſt, Mayor, by Jo./Taylor, the Water Poet, 1634—Ditto of Sir Maurice Abbot, by/ Tho. Heywood, 1638—Ditto of Henry Garway, by Heywood,/ 1639. It is possible that this is the same copy that now resides in the John Rylands Library ( Finlayson 118; Bibliotheca Westiana 225).
TEI:history.TEI:acquisition: Acquired by the John Rylands Library at the purchase of the Spencer Collection in 1892.
